💡 Core Idea (VERY IMPORTANT — don’t miss this)

This is a connected components problem.

🔥 Key Observation:

Two passwords are equivalent if:

They share at least one common character
OR they are connected through a chain of such passwords

👉 This is exactly graph connectivity

🧠 Modeling

Think like this:

Each character (a–z) = node
Each password connects all its characters

Example:
"abc" → connect a-b, b-c, a-c

So passwords create edges between characters

🎯 Final Insight
Each connected component of characters = one group of equivalent passwords
To guarantee access → pick 1 password per component

👉 Answer = number of connected components (that actually appear)

⚡ Approach
Use DSU (Union-Find) on 26 characters
For each string:
Union all its characters
Track which characters appear
Count unique parents of those characters
🚀 Code (C++)
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

vector<int> parent(26);

int find(int x) {
    if (parent[x] == x) return x;
    return parent[x] = find(parent[x]);
}

void unite(int a, int b) {
    a = find(a);
    b = find(b);
    if (a != b) parent[a] = b;
}

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(NULL);

    int n;
    cin >> n;

    // initialize DSU
    for (int i = 0; i < 26; i++) parent[i] = i;

    vector<bool> used(26, false);

    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        string s;
        cin >> s;

        for (char c : s) {
            used[c - 'a'] = true;
        }

        // union all chars in string
        for (int j = 1; j < s.size(); j++) {
            unite(s[0] - 'a', s[j] - 'a');
        }
    }

    set<int> components;

    for (int i = 0; i < 26; i++) {
        if (used[i]) {
            components.insert(find(i));
        }
    }

    cout << components.size() << "\n";
}
⚡ Complexity
DSU operations: O(total characters α(26)) ≈ O(n)
Works easily within constraints
🧠 Intuition Recap (1 line)

👉 Characters connect → components form → answer = number of components
